{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528112"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:37:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:37:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14264"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14264"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.08,0.63,0.09,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6959"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54237"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6959"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14264"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39717"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1154"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16299"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54237"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of a painful right eye.  She noticed it becoming increasingly painful and red when in the garden three days prior, and finds bright light uncomfortable so has been wearing her sunglasses inside.  She wears glasses and noticed that it has been harder to see clearly with her right eye, despite having seen the Optometrist recently for a routine review.  She has hayfever and takes regular oral antihistamines. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable with sunglasses on. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Ophthalmological examination reveals conjunctival injection, a miotic pupil, and cells and flare in the anterior chamber of the right eye. Visual acuity in the right eye is 6/12, compared to 6/6 in the left eye. Intraocular pressure is normal in both eyes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral prednisolone","Intravitreal triamcinolone injection","Topical prednisolone and cyclopentolate","Topical moxifloxacin","Oral acyclovir"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with acute anterior uveitis (acute iritis) as demonstrated by the eye pain, conjunctival injection, photophobia, miosis, and cells and flare in the anterior chamber. The most appropriate initial management for this condition is \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical prednisolone and cyclopentolate\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical prednisolone 1%\u003C/strong\u003E (a corticosteroid) helps to reduce inflammation in the anterior chamber. The frequency of administration depends on the severity of the inflammation, but it is typically started at a high frequency (e.g., every 1-2 hours) and then tapered as the condition improves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECyclopentolate\u003C/strong\u003E (a cycloplegic agent) is used in conjunction with the topical steroid. It paralyses the ciliary muscle, which helps to prevent the formation of posterior synechiae (adhesions between the iris and lens) and reduces pain by preventing ciliary muscle spasm. It also dilates the pupil, which can help break any early synechiae that may have formed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary in cases of severe or bilateral anterior uveitis, or if the condition is not responding to topical treatment. However, it is not typically the first-line treatment for a case of unilateral anterior uveitis as described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravitreal triamcinolone injection\u003C/strong\u003E is a treatment sometimes used for posterior uveitis or macular oedema, but it is not appropriate as initial management for anterior uveitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical moxifloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E is an antibiotic eye drop used to treat bacterial conjunctivitis or keratitis.  Whilst the presence of conjunctival injection and discomfort is similar, there would be no miosis seen and no change in visual acuity. It would not be effective in treating the inflammation associated with anterior uveitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral acyclovir\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if there was suspicion of herpetic uveitis, but this would typically present with other features such as corneal involvement or vesicular skin lesions, which are not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to the topical treatments, the patient should be referred urgently to an ophthalmologist for further evaluation and management. This may include investigations to determine any underlying cause of the uveitis, such as autoimmune conditions or infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Topical corticosteroids and cyclopegic agents are the mainstay of treatment for acute anterior uveitis.","Systemic corticosteroids may be necessary for severe or bilateral anterior uveitis."],"references":["Read R, Feldman B, Tsakiris K et al. Anterior Uveitis. Eye Wiki. 2022. Available at: https://eyewiki.org/Acute_Anterior_Uveitis","Agrawal RV, Murthy S, Sangwan V, Biswas J. Current approach in diagnosis and management of anterior uveitis. Indian J Ophthalmol. 2010 Jan-Feb;58(1):11-9. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2841369/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39717"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14264"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39717"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-01T19:29:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-01T19:30:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6959"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54237"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attribu